<br>
According to a sociologist I heard once, nothing beneficial for a member of a minority can be considered racist.  Racism requires two things:  Power (Ie that of the Majority [ie. white]) and discrimination.  Doing something racist consists of targeting a member of a minority, and committing an act against that person which further marginalizes them (pushes them away from power, society, you name it).  It is impossible for a white person to be pushed away from those centers, as they are inherently part of those centers... the only way for a white person to not be racist, is to in fact actively push away from those centers themselves.<br>
<br>
So.. a member of a minority is incapable of being racist, because that intones some degree of social power.  A white person however, can be racist... in fact, most people are, even if they don't know it.  <br>
<br>
The analogy to describe this is as such- imagine an airport terminal with those really long, moving walkways.  The &quot;terminal&quot; corridor is life/social status, and as people move down the terminal, they get ahead.  Minorities cannot ride the moving walkways, they must walk.  White people always ride down the moving walkways.  Even when standing still (not directly/actively using their racial benefits in daily life) they still move as fast as many of the minority members that have to walk.  The white people that stand have the benefit of their color and the social structures they have created around color.  The white people that actively use their position in society book it down the terminal faster than most minority members could sprinting like mad.<br>
<br>
Something like affirmative action is akin to giving a sort of moving walkway to everyone.  It might seem like a blatent way of giving an advantage to minorities, but it still is insignificant in comparison to the moving walkways members of the majority enjoy (even if they aren't aware of it- and just stand).  Affirmative action stops at a paycheck in terms of the advantage it gives minorities... but think of the advantages the majority has regardless of policies.  <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uyamori.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yamori</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theunholytrinity.org/cracks_smileys/contrib/dvv/boom.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Annoying Bastard</span><br>  Posts: 1181<br> <font color=#333333>(2/10/02 5:23:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/yamorisennin/magus1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The affirmative action...</span><hr size=1> Well, I do agree that it isn't racism, since the dictionary definition, as you said, says only a majority can be racist...<br>
