<br>
&quot;A policy or a program that seeks to redress past discrimination through active measures to ensure equal opportunity, as in education and employment.&quot;<br>
<br>
the term &quot;forcing&quot; is just an issue of stance, not fact.  I could just as easily place the term &quot;helping.&quot;  Affirmative action does not force people to spend their money hiring people they do not want.  The purpose of AA is to ensure equal opportunity, as stated above.<br>
<br>
If the US could come up with a policy that caused a color-blind people, no doubt there would be a part of the population addressing that as well.  Americans have as much right to like one person more than another, or find their own preferences through their cultural and moral traditions.  It seems clear that asking people to be color-blind is as ineffectual as telling the wind to change directions.<br>
<br>
Even if we did set up a sort of color-blind system, the system would still be formed by the current majority, off of the system founded by that same majority.  In every instance or situation beyond a Fresh Prince of Bel-Air sitcom environment can people find numerous examples of how the system denies opportunities for members of minorities.  AA is simply a means to ensure that the system works for them instead of against them.  It is blatent, it is obvious and yes, a good number of people above the &quot;glass ceiling&quot; hate it, but that's non-issue.  A good chunk of the wealth in america was made at the hands of slaves, a good number of the businesses were NINA...  The majority has spent centuries trying to keep minorities away from &quot;their&quot; money (which in many philosophical, sociological, and economic perspectives is Not)... whether it be kings and surfs, or tycoons and laborers.  Never say a mogul's money is his own, policy and populace have fought for years to regain some fraction of the profits made by the few, and to use such argumentation against AA simply reinforces the ideal that inequality is fostered by our economics and fundamental to our purpose as a nation- to support the rich in favor of the poor.<br>
<br>
